Dan @drettenmaier came to me with knee pain that had been frustrating him for the past 5 years! In this video you’ll see his evaluation, part of his treatment & see how he’s doing today!
.
Takeaway: there is no one size fits all method to fixing knee pain. You must evaluate (especially looking at the area above & below the site of pain) and create an individualized plan to address what you find while slowly rebuilding capacity. Remember, a knees over toes position is nothing to fear! However we must understand context and sometimes need to take a step back in order to eventually move forward.
.
Shout out to Dan for putting in the wok to fix this injury & to @3d4medical with the Complete Anatomy app visual of the body in today’s post.

One of my favorite warm ups before squatting is to use a band for some slow bodyweight squats. I'll often throw a 1-1/2 motion into the mix. The goal with this exercise is to get your hips engaged equally on both sides before getting under the barbell. If you don't have symmetrical engagement in your hips you'll often see twists or shifts when lifting.📝
.

The traditional medical model will try to look at a scan of your back and determine what they see as “abnormal” to be the exact cause of pain. However, there is a ton of research that shows just because you find a problem on MRI does not mean it’s the exact cause of pain. 
.
So what do we do?  We fit your symptoms into a movement diagnosis category! This is something I learned from renowned back expert @backfitpro. A movement diagnosis tells you what motions, postures and loads to avoid in the short term so we don’t continue your pain. It doesn’t matter how many corrective exercises or stability drills you do, if you continue to push into your trigger for pain, it usually won’t get better on it’s own. 
.
The process of limiting individual movement triggers has been shown in research to help reduce pain effectively. It’s not creating fear of movement but rather empowering you to understand your injury so you can take control of the rehab process. 
.
Shout out to @krispy_kremez for being my patient model in this video!

One method to help fix a hip shift when squatting is to use a band around the hips, attempting to pull the lifter into more shift. Doing so creates a reaction in the body that can help some find better balance like this young powerlifter who came to me with hip pain. 
.
1️⃣If you’re dealing with a hip shift, be sure to also check out my YouTube video “how to fix a hip shift” and try the mobility test I share there as well!
2️⃣If you’d like to see the longer version of my work with this young powerlifter @tate.fegley, check out my YouTube video “11 year old powerlifter fixes injury & crushes big weight.”

This is a novel exercise to help enhance shoulder stability when lifting overhead - something I first learned from @benlustigphysiotherapy. I’ve used it many times in the past half year with patients of mine recovering from shoulder pain who need more stability when lifting overhead and have seen tremendous improvements. 
.
When to use: be sure to try the test I showed in this video first!!!! If you’re weak - then try & retest to see if this is helpful for you. Remember, “corrective exercises” are only helpful if used in the right situation. Never do an exercise just because it looks cool on social media.😉
.
Shout out to @benlustigphysiotherapy for sharing this exercise with me & @edpilgrimdpt for being my model athlete today. Also shout out to @3d4medical with the Complete Anatomy app for the visual of the body & @olychad for his lifting demos.

During Luke’s injury rehab with me, we ran into a pretty significant limitation in ankle mobility. Now we were definitely seeing some progress with banded joint mobilizations, stretching and soft tissue work with rolling, but he was still a little off balance in his bottom squat position.📝
.
Now when I see problems like this – we often look at the ankle joint  especially the motion of knee moving over the toe – a motion called dorsiflexion – but we need to also look at the motions that occur in other planes like rotation and glide.✅
.
I assessed his lateral shin motion with this movement. Clearly very different on his injury side. This prompted me to test his tibial rotation and as you can see he has much less rotation on his injured side.📝
.
I suggested he use this banded drill. With the band placed under the base of his 1st toe, he tensioned the band and drove his knee out to the side – feeling his glutes working hard and held for 10”. Now if you don’t keep a stable foot during this motion the band will snap out from under your foot.❌ .
We also worked on trying to improve lateral tibial glide, holding the foot down in place and pushing the knee to the side and holding for a few seconds. After performing those you can see a huge difference in ankle mobility.🙌🏼 .
So the next week when we were squatting, I noted he was a little off balance in his bottom position – with the bar shooting out over his toes. We did one more set of tibial rotation drills and the very next see you can see a large difference – now more balanced and able to sit down with the bar over his mid foot.🙌🏼
.
Shout out to @thelukemeredith for putting in the hard work during rehab, you're doing such great work man. Also thank you to @3d4medical with the compete anatomy app for the visual of the body today. .

Recently @martinslicis deadlifted 605 lbs (275kg) for 18 reps without a belt! Today I wanted to share a quick tip Martins has for performing the touch & go deadlift he’s performing (the clip is from our YouTube video collaboration “The Ultimate Deadlift Tutorial”).📲
.
When doing touch & go deadlifts think: squat the bar to the knees, then RDL to the standing position. Then reverse it down the opposite way. RDL to the knee, then squat the bar down GENTLY TAP THE GROUND & repeat! Do NOT bounce the bar hard off the ground. 
.
This manner of deadlifting increases time under tension as you have to control the weight back down to the ground - an excellent method of improving strength & technique capacity!
.
Shout out @martinslicis for being such a great example of how to approach training & @romarkweiss for the excellent videography.

node.text:
What pains/injuries are you currently dealing with? Let me know in the comment section so I can make content to help you!👇🏼
.
Most injuries we sustain while lifting are the result of cumulative micro trauma sustained from repetitive technique errors & suboptimal programming that doesn’t allow the body to recover from the weights we lift. This means if you have a poor lift where your knees cave in or a bad deadlift where your back rounds uncontrollably - your likelihood of injury is very low. However, if you continue to allow problems to occur while pushing big weights, over time your risk of injury increases. 
.
What is pain? What there are many reasons for developing pain - when it comes to the majority of cases when lifting, it’s a signal you body needs a change. It is not an impending signal of doom or telling you that you are fragile BUT it is a signal you want to understand and not ignore. Always ask why. 
.
Think of pain when lifting like a check engine light in your car. It doesn’t mean your engine is going to break down this second or that you have to stop driving this second or else!!! But it is saying, “check something out” - it’s alerting you to take a look and see what may not be operating optimally for the long term “health” of the machine. 
.
If you’re currently dealing with back pain, elbow pain, shoulder issues or knee issues - I’ve got a ton of free content on my website squatuniversity.com and on my YouTube to help you screen your body and find your individual reasons for injury so you can rebuild and get back to doing the things you love to do.

Are your shoes smashing your toes together or shaped like feet?🤔You were born with your toes as the widest part of your foot - but most major shoe brands today build shoes that come to a point and smash your toes together. It may surprise some of you that despite the billions of dollars spent by these major brands in R&D to create their shoes - they overwhelmingly create shoes that are built for fashion & not help your foot function as it was designed. A shoe that does less TO your foot is best FOR your foot. 
.
It’s estimated that roughly 90% of people are wearing shoes that are way too narrow for their foot (per Dr. Ray McClanahan of @correcttoes). A narrow toe box hinders your foots ability to stabilize itself (making it harder to maintain balance/control of our lower body when lifting) & increases risk of foot problems (bunions, plantar fasciitis, etc). 
.
TAKEAWAY: if you are serious about how well you move in the gym & in life…and also want to keep your body healthy for as long as you live, you NEED to get out of these narrow shoes & start wearing those that are foot shaped (a few examples are @bearfootshoes, @vivobarefoot, @xeroshoes, @feelgrounds & @lemsshoes).
.
Want to learn more? Check out my YouTube video “Why you should wear barefoot shoes.”📲 or my prior podcast with Dr. McClanahan “Why your shoes suck.”📲

node.text:
Working TOWARDS perfection & WAITING for perfection are two different things. Our goal as strength athletes is to lift the most amount of weight in competition. Therefore we MUST progressively overload with heavy weights in training to gain strength. The quality of our technique during this time dictates how efficiently we lift & is a big factor in dictating our risk of injury long term. Here’s a easy way to think about this: 
.
Optimal: this is where we ideally want to be. While we are all still a “work in progress” this category represents those with very small technical errors that usually only appear with heaviest weights. Great quality technique during lifts allows for more volume & intensity to be handled with the athlete finding longevity in their sport at the same time. 
.
Good: this means the athlete moves well enough to progressively overload. While there are some technical errors that limits efficiency, they are NOT major breakdowns. If proper programming is used, the small amount of heavy lifts where technique breaks down keeps the injury risk low. These athletes need to work each day to improve technique BUT are able to continue loading & progressing strength. 
.
Poor: this group represents major breakdowns that need to be addressed before progressive loading. While there is no “one perfect technique” that works for everyone - that does NOT mean we should accept major knee cave or uncontrolled back rounding at moderate weights. Poor technique over time increases risk of injury. This DOES NOT mean a hip shift or knee cave automatically leads to injury at the time of breakdown. BUT over time with repetition after repetition it increases risk. These athletes need to take a step back and focus on the fundamentals before going forward. Doing so will improve their eventual efficiency of lifting & longevity in the sport. 
.
Remember, we’re all “works in progress” - no one is perfect but we are always striving.

node.text:
Despite what some insta-trainers may tell you, training the core doesn’t mean we have to isolate the ab muscles with the classic sit-up, twists or side bends. In fact, spending countless hours doing these exercises doesn’t help you move better or lift bigger weights at all!🤯
.
While exercises like Russian twists, sit-ups or back extensions from a GHD machine may be great at increasing strength, they do little to increase core stiffness.
.
In order to enhance the quality of stiffness, one must train the core differently with isometrics, like performing a bent over row with the emphasis to move about the hip to get into position & keep the core braced while you perform the row.👍🏼
.
When we train the core this way, we actually learn how to create the body’s “natural weightlifting belt” and enhance stability in a way that carries over to improved performance!!🏋🏼‍♀️
.
Final thoughts: stop wasting your time “doing abs” and focus on creating core stability. If you want to get that 6-pack, think about optimizing you’re diet ... as they say “6-packs are made in the kitchen.”😉

Here’s a recent complex I recently performed with the guidance of 2x Olympian @olychad. I’m always in constant pursuit of perfection & while I know I’ll never get there, I love the climb. Currently I’m working to maintain my straight elbows through full extension while fully extending onto my toes. Even though I started competing in Olympic weightlifting back in 2005 - I still have things in my own lifting to work on just like you. So the cues Chad gave me was to flex my triceps to maintain a long arm position during the pull & to slow my lift down slightly and feel for that full ankle extension up onto my toes - and it’s definitely been helping. 
.
As strength athletes, it’s not about lifting heavy day in and day out. While max out day is always fun, a LARGE portion of training progress comes from working on improving movement quality with sub-max lifts. 
.
Thank you @olychad for the help in my lifts (remember, every coach still needs their own coach too😉). If you’re not following him yet - get on it.

Dan @drettenmaier came to me with knee pain that had been frustrating him for the past 5 years! In this video you’ll see his evaluation, part of his treatment & see how he’s doing today!
.
Takeaway: there is no one size fits all method to fixing knee pain. You must evaluate (especially looking at the area above & below the site of pain) and create an individualized plan to address what you find while slowly rebuilding capacity. Remember, a knees over toes position is nothing to fear! However we must understand context and sometimes need to take a step back in order to eventually move forward.
.
Shout out to Dan for putting in the wok to fix this injury & to @3d4medical with the Complete Anatomy app visual of the body in today’s post.

One of the things that saddens me the most is when I talk to patients of mine who give me the story, “well I used to lift when I was younger.” The idea that lifting weights & pushing your body is only something you do when young is WRONG. It is something for LIFE. 
.
While you may not be setting new personal records in your 60s compared to when you were 25 that doesn’t mean strength training should be any less a part of your life. Strength allows you to build capacity for everyday tasks such as lifting a box in your garage, walking up stairs & getting off the toilet (not a joke, literally this is something many have issues with as they age).
.
